MySQL-DDL COMMANDS
CREATE TABLE
ALTER TABLE
DROP TABLE
TRUNCATE TABLE

Lets Start....

 show databases; used to show all databases.
 show tables; used to show all tables in current database.
 create database_name; used to create a database
 use database_name; used to set as the current database.
 desc table_name; used to show description of a table

1. CREATE COMMAND

 The CREATE TABLE statement is used to create a new table in a database.
 The CREATE DATABASE statement is used to create a new DATABSE
 Syntax:
 CREATE DATABASE databsename;
 CREATE TABLE table_name (
column1 datatype,
column2 datatype,
column3 datatype,
....
);

 CREATE DATABASE ksb;
 CREATE TABLE student( name varchar(20), roll int);

Experiments: CREATE
 Create a table STUDENT having following fields: roll_no, name, age, address
 Mysql> CREATE TABLE student (roll_no INT, name VARCHAR(15), age int,
address VARCHAR (50));
 Create a table EMPLOYEE have the following fields: Emp_id, emp_name,
salary. Emp_is is primary key.
 Mysql> CREATE TABLE employee( emp_id INT PRIMARY KEY, name
VARCHAR(20), salary DECIMAL(5,2));
 Create a table BOOK having the following fields:
 book_no –primary key
 Book_name - not null
 Serial no. -unique
 Author_name -
 Price -set as default ‘0’
 Mysql>create table book(book_no int primary key, book_name varchar(20)
not null, sl_no int unique, author_name varchar(20), price decimal(3,2)
default '0');

 Create a table person have following fields:
 P_id –autoincrement
 Pname – notnull
 Dob
 Mysql> create table person (p_id int primary key auto_increment, p_name
varchar(20), dob date);

2. ALTER Command

 The ALTER TABLE statement is used to add, delete, or modify columns in an
existing table.
 The ALTER TABLE statement is also used to add and drop various constraints
on an existing table.

2.1 ALTER TABLE - ADD Column

 Syntax:
 ALTER TABLE table_name ADD column_name datatype;
 Eg: add a colum Email to the table student.
 Mysql> ALTER TABLE student ADD Email varchar(255);
 Add a colum dob to the table student;

2.2 ALTER TABLE - DROP COLUMN

 To delete a column in a table
 Syntax:
 ALTER TABLE table_name DROP COLUMN column_name;
 Eg: drop the column email from the table student;
 mysql> ALTER TABLE student DROP COLUMN Email;

2.3 ALTER TABLE - ALTER/MODIFY COLUMN

 To change the data type of a column in a table,
 Syntax:
 ALTER TABLE table_name MODIFY COLUMN column_name datatype;
 Eg: Change the datatype of the column name as varchar (50)
 Mysql>ALTER TABLE student MODIFY COLUMN name varchar(50);
 Eg: Change the data type of the dob in year.

3. DROP COMMAND

 The DROP TABLE statement is used to drop an existing table in a database.
 Syntax:
 DROP TABLE table_name;
 Eg:
 Mysql> DROP TABLE student;

4. TRUNCATE COMMAND

 Delete all rows in a table’
 Syntax:
 TRUNCATE tablename;
 Eg:
 TRUNCATE STUDENT;

 Create a table EMPLOYEE having following field:

 Emp_id...INT
 Emp_name----VARCHAR(15)
 Salary ---DECIMAL(8,2)
 Dob-----DATE









DDL-EXTRA QUERIES

ALTER command

 ADD, DROP, MODIFY, CHANGE columns, constraints

mysql> ALTER TABLE student ADD age INT;
ALTER TABLE student DROP age;
ALTER TABLE student ADD age INT FIRST;
ALTER TABLE student DROP age;
ALTER TABLE student ADD age INT AFTER name;

 ALTER TABLE student
ADD last_name varchar(40) NOT NULL
AFTER age,
ADD first_name varchar(35) NULL
AFTER last_name;

 mysql> ALTER TABLE student MODIFY last_name
CHAR(10);
 mysql> ALTER TABLE student CHANGE last_name lname
BIGINT;

 mysql> ALTER TABLE student MODIFY age INT NOT NULL
DEFAULT 1;
 ALTER TABLE student ALTER age SET DEFAULT 10;
 ALTER TABLE student ALTER age DROP DEFAULT;
 mysql> ALTER TABLE student RENAME TO teacher;

Create constraints using create
command

 CREATE TABLE table_name
 (
 column1 datatype [ NULL | NOT NULL ],
 column2 datatype [ NULL | NOT NULL ],
 ...
 CONSTRAINT constraint_name UNIQUE (uc_col1, uc_col2, ... uc_col_n)
 );
 Eg: create table student (roll int, name varchar(10), age int, adhar int,
constraint c1 unique(age,adhar), constraint c2 primary key(roll));

ADD constraints using ALTER command

 ALTER TABLE student ADD CONSTRAINT c1 UNIQUE
(last_name, first_name);
 here c1 is the constraint name.
 ALTER TABLE student ADD CONSTRAINT c2 PRIMARY KEY
(ID);
 ALTER TABLE student ADD CONSTRAINT c3 CHECK
(age>20);

3 ways to add constraints:

1.Create table student (roll int primary key, name
varchar(10), age int);
2.Create table student (roll int, name varchar(10),
age int, constraint c1 primary key (roll));
3.Alter table student add constraint c1 primary
key (roll);

Drop constraints

 ALTER TABLE STUDENT DROP PRIMARY KEY;

 OR

 ALTER TABLE STUDENT DROP CONSTRAINT C1;
 ALTER TABLE table_name DROP INDEX c2;
 ALTER TABLE Orders DROP FOREIGN KEY c4;
 ALTER TABLE Persons DROP CHECK c3;
 ALTER TABLE STUDENT MODIFY AGE INT NULL; (drop null constraint)

Rename table

 ALTER TABLE <table_old name> RENAME TO <new_name>;

Create TEMPORARY table

 Temporary Table that allows us to keep temporary data.
 mysql> CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE table_name (
column_1, column_2, ..., table_constraints
);
 eg: Mysql> CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE temporary_table_name SELECT *
FROM original_table_name ;
 mysql> CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE Students( student_name VARCHAR(40) N
OT NULL, total_marks DECIMAL(12,2) NOT NULL DEFAULT 0.00, total_subjects I
NT;

Create DUPLICATE table

 Copying data of an existing table into a new table is very useful in a
situation like backing up data in table failure.
 CREATE TABLE new_table_name
SELECT column1, column2, column3
FROM existing_table_name;
 Eg: CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS duplicate_table SELECT * FROM
original_table;

